AMEND S e n ate Bill No. 1326* House Bill No. 1380
by deleting all language after the enacting clause and substituting:
SECTION 1. Tennessee Code Annotated, Section 67-5-702, is amended by adding the
following language as a new subsection (g):
(1) Notwithstanding this section and § 67-5-701, the collecting official or the
division of property assessments is not required to request documentation verifying the
applicant's income if:
(A) The applicant is eighty (80) years of age or older;
(B) One (1) of the following is satisfied:
(i) The applicant has applied for and received property tax relief
pursuant to this section for the immediately preceding five (5) consecutive
years for the same place of residence; or
(ii) The applicant has been a co-owner of the same parcel for the
immediately preceding five (5) consecutive years in which another co-
owner applied for and received tax relief under this section for each of
those five (5) years;
(C) The annual income attributable to the applicant does not exceed the
annually adjusted income threshold described in subdivision (a)(2); and
(D) The applicant meets all other non-income-related criteria for
eligibility.
(2) Notwithstanding subdivision (g)(1), the collecting official or the division of
property assessments may request documentation verifying incomes of other individuals
HA1144
016907
- 1 -

that are attributable to the applicant under subdivision (a)(2) or documentation related to
non-income eligibility criteria under this section and § 67-5-701.
(3) Notwithstanding subdivision (g)(1), to remain eligible for the tax relief
program, the applicant must continue to annually complete and submit the tax relief
application to the collecting official, as required by § 67-5-701(c). The division of
property assessments shall develop a simplified reapplication process for applicants
described in this subsection (g) that allows the applicant to indicate whether the
applicant meets the income and non-income-related requirements by checking a box or
boxes.
SECTION 2. This act takes effect upon becoming a law, the public welfare requiring it.
